# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aberdeen-journals
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-citizen] The ***Aberdeen Citizen*** was a weekly free newspaper in Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-citizen] Launched on 26 August 1989 as the ***Aberdeen Herald & Post***, it succeeded the *Aberdeen Post* and was re-launched as its most recent title in 2002.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-citizen] It was the highest distributed free newspaper in Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-citizen] It provided a round-up of the week's community news, sport and events to over 75,000 households in the city and surrounding areas.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-citizen] "We have a good team spirit at the *Aberdeen Citizen* and we work together to make sure that every resident in Aberdeen City and Shire gets their paper!" The *Aberdeen Citizen* expanded progressively since its launch and won "The Best Free Newspaper In Scotland" Award.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-citizen] In 2002, the Office of Fair Trading handed Aberdeen Journals a fine for predatory pricing for advertising in the *Citizen*.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-citizen] Its then-owners, Northcliffe Newspapers, expressed disappointment with the ruling.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-citizen] The paper's print version ceased publication on 23 May 2018.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-citizen] However, its online version has been merged with *The Press and Journal*.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-journals] The company publishes *The Press and Journal*, the *Evening Express*, the *Aberdeen Citizen* and *Scot-Ads* newspapers.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-journals] It was owned by Northcliffe Newspapers Group, which is owned by Daily Mail & General Trust from 1995 until 2006, when Aberdeen Journals was sold to Dundee based D.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-journals] It was published on a weekly basis for 128 years until August 1876, when it became a daily newspaper.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-journals] In November 1922, the paper was renamed T*he Aberdeen Press & Journal* when its parent firm joined forces with the *Free Press*.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-journals] *The Press & Journal*, often called the *P&J*, is a daily morning regional newspaper.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-journals] It is printed 6 days a week as a compact.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-journals] The Press & Journal produces 6 geographic editions.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-journals] The current editor of *The Press and Journal* is Frank O’Donnell.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-journals] The *Evening Express* is a daily local evening newspaper which was first published in 20 January 1879.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-journals] The current editor of the *Evening Express* is Craig Walker.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen received royal burgh status from David I of Scotland (1124–1153), which transformed the city economically.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The traditional industries of fishing, paper-making, shipbuilding, and textiles have been overtaken by the oil industry and Aberdeen's seaport.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Heliport is one of the busiest commercial heliports in the world, and the seaport is the largest in the north-east part of Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] A university town, the city is known for the University of Aberdeen, founded in 1495 as King's College, the fifth oldest university in the English-speaking world and located in Old Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] During the mid-18th to mid-20th centuries, Aberdeen's buildings incorporated locally quarried grey granite, which may sparkle like silver because of its high mica content.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Since the discovery of North Sea oil in 1969, Aberdeen has been known as the offshore **oil capital of Europe**.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Based upon the discovery of prehistoric villages around the mouths of the rivers Dee and Don, the area around Aberdeen is thought to have been settled for at least 6,000 years.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The name given to Aberdeen translates as 'mouth of the river Don', and is recorded as Aberdon in 1172 and Aberden in c.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The first element of the name is the Pictish word *aber* 'river mouth'.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The second element is from the Celtic river goddess Devona.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is usually described as within the historical Pictish territory and became Gaelic-speaking at some time in the medieval period.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Old Aberdeen is the approximate location of Aberdon, the first settlement of Aberdeen; this literally means "the mouth of the Don".
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The Celtic word *aber* means "river mouth", as in modern Welsh (Aberystwyth, Aberdare, Aberbeeg etc.).
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Gaelic name is *Obar Dheathain* (variation: *Obairreadhain*; **obar* presumably being a loan from the earlier Pictish; the Gaelic term is *inbhir*), and in Latin, the Romans referred to the river as *Devana*.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Medieval (or Ecclesiastical) Latin has it as *Aberdonia*.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The local Doric pronunciation, [ˌeːbərˈdin] ⓘ or [ˈeːbərdin] ⓘ (with a long *ay* sound), is frequently rendered *Aiberdeen* or *Aiberdein*.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen area has seen human settlement for at least 8,000 years.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The city began as two separate burghs: Old Aberdeen at the mouth of the river Don; and New Aberdeen, a fishing and trading settlement, where the Denburn waterway entered the river Dee estuary.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The earliest charter was granted by William the Lion in 1179 and confirmed the corporate rights granted by David I.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] In 1214, Aberdeen Burgesses were granted a Royal Charter by Alexander II of Scotland giving them the sole right to form a Guild.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] This body exercised power in the composition of the local council, and the affairs of the town.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The Burgesses of the Guild were an integral part of the council for more than 700 years and played a considerable role in the growth and development of Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] In 1319, the Great Charter of Robert the Bruce transformed Aberdeen into a property-owning and financially independent community.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Granted with it was the nearby Forest of Stocket, whose income formed the basis for the city's Common Good Fund which still benefits Aberdonians.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of Scottish Independence, Aberdeen was under English rule, so Robert the Bruce laid siege to Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308, followed by executing the English garrison.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The city was burned by Edward III of England in 1336, but was rebuilt and extended.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The city was strongly fortified to prevent attacks by neighbouring lords, but the gates were removed by 1770.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's medieval council registers survive from 1398 onwards and are exceptional for their quantity and continuity among surviving Scottish burgh records.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The earliest eight volumes, from 1398 to 1511, have been included in the UNESCO UK Memory of the World Register, and have been edited in a digital edition.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of the Three Kingdoms of 1644 to 1647 the city was plundered by both sides.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] In 1644, it was taken and ransacked by Royalist troops after the Battle of Aberdeen and two years later it was stormed by a Royalist force under the command of the George Gordon, 2nd Marquess of Huntly.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] An outbreak of bubonic plague over 1687 and 1688 killed 8.5% of the population, adding to the economic and demographic damage caused by war.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] In the 18th century, a new Town Hall was built and the first social services appeared with the Aberdeen Infirmary at Woolmanhill in 1739 and the Aberdeen Lunatic Asylum in 1800.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The expensive infrastructure works led to the city becoming bankrupt in 1817 during the Post-Napoleonic depression, an economic downturn immediately after the Napoleonic Wars; but the city's prosperity later recovered.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The increasing economic importance of Aberdeen and the development of the shipbuilding and fishing industries led to the construction of the present harbour including Victoria Dock and the South Breakwater, and the extension of the North Pier.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Gas street lighting arrived in 1824 and an enhanced water supply appeared in 1830 when water was pumped from the Dee to a reservoir in Union Place.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] An underground sewer system replaced open sewers in 1865.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The city absorbed the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee in 1891.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Over the course of World War II Aberdeen was attacked 32 times by the German Luftwaffe.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] One of the most devastating attacks was on Wednesday 21 April 1943 when 29 Luftwaffe Dornier 217s flying from Stavanger, Norway attacked the city between the hours of 22:17 and 23:04.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] A total of 98 civilians and 27 servicemen were killed, along with 12,000 houses damaged, after a mixture of 127 Incendiary, High Explosive and Cluster bombs were dropped on the city in one night.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Two books written in 2018 and 2022 using bombing records held in London identified that unexploded bombs from the 1943 raid were found in the 1950s and 1980s making the bombs dropped 129 in total.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Damage from the raid can still be seen in some parts of Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The arms and banner of the city show three silver towers on red.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] This motif dates from at least the time of Robert the Bruce and represents the buildings that stood on the three hills of medieval Aberdeen: Aberdeen Castle on Castle Hill (today's Castlegate); the city gate on Port Hill; and a church on St Catherine's Hill (now levelled).
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] "Bon Accord" is the motto of the city and is French for "Good Agreement".
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Legend tells that its use dates from a password used by Robert the Bruce during the 14th century Wars of Scottish Independence, when he and his men laid siege to the English-held Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] It is still widely present in the city, throughout street names, business names and the city's Bon Accord shopping mall.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The shield in the coat of arms is supported by two leopards.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] A local magazine is called the "Leopard" and, when Union Bridge was widened in the 20th century, small statues of the creature in a sitting position were cast and placed on top of the railing posts (known locally as Kelly's Cats).
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The city's toast is "Happy to meet, sorry to part, happy to meet again".
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] In 2012, HSBC named Aberdeen as a leading business hub and one of eight 'super cities' spearheading the UK's economy, marking it as the only city in Scotland so designated.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] In 2018, Aberdeen was found to be the best city in the UK to start a business in a study released by card payment firm Paymentsense.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen City is one of 32 council areas of Scotland, administered by Aberdeen City Council.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The council meets at Aberdeen Town House and has its main offices in the adjoining Marischal College.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The civic head and chair of the council is the Lord Provost.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The council area is also divided into 30 community council areas, 29 of which had community councils operating as at August 2024.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The first burgh of Aberdeen, covering just the New Aberdeen area near the mouth of the Dee, was created by David I (reigned 1124–1153).
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Neighbouring Old Aberdeen to the north was subsequently made a separate burgh in 1489.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The burgh of Aberdeen was governed by a corporation, also known as the town council.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] As Aberdeen grew, the council's powers were inadequate to cater for the needs of the growing urban area.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] A separate police commission was established in 1795 with powers to levy taxes and provide infrastructure ('police' in this context being its older meaning of civic government rather than law enforcement).
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The first police commission was short-lived, but it was resurrected in 1818 after the town council went bankrupt in 1817.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] From 1818 until 1871 there was a dual system of local government, with the town council and police commission having different roles in Aberdeen's administration.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The police commission was eventually abolished in 1871 and its functions absorbed by the town council.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] In 1891 the city boundaries were significantly enlarged, absorbing the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside, plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The act of parliament which expanded the burgh also confirmed that Aberdeen was entitled to be called a city; it had commonly been described as a city prior to that, but (like most Scottish cities) without official recognition.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Following the absorption of Torry in 1891, the city boundaries straddled the counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was made a county of itself in 1899.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] In 1975 the burgh was replaced by the larger City of Aberdeen district within the Grampian region.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Further local government reforms in 1996 replaced the districts and regions created in 1975 with council areas; the pre-1996 City of Aberdeen district became the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] In the Scottish Parliament, the city is represented by three constituencies with different boundaries: Aberdeen Central and Aberdeen Donside are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Deeside and North Kincardine includes the North Kincardine ward of Aberdeenshire Council.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] A further seven MSPs are elected as part of the North East Scotland electoral region.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] In the European Parliament the city was represented by six MEPs as part of the all-inclusive Scotland constituency.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is represented in the Parliament of the United Kingdom by two constituencies, Aberdeen North and Aberdeen South, which are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Being situated between two river mouths, the city has little natural exposure of bedrock.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The small amount of geophysics done, and occasional building-related exposures, combined with small exposures in the banks of the River Don, suggest that it is actually sited on an inlier of Devonian "Old Red" sandstones and silts.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The city extends to 186 km2 (72 sq mi), and includes the former burghs of Old Aberdeen, New Aberdeen, Woodside and the Torry area to the south of River Dee.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] In 2024, this gave the city a population density of 1,249 inhabitants per square kilometre (3,230/sq mi).
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The city is built on many hills, with the original beginnings of the city growing from Castle Hill, St.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] When compared to mainland Europe, Aberdeen is further north than almost all of Denmark and plenty of southern Sweden, being just south of Gothenburg in terms of latitude.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen features an oceanic climate (Köppen *Cfb*), with far milder winter temperatures than one might expect for its northern location.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] However, statistically speaking, it is still the coldest city in the UK.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] During the winter, especially throughout December, the length of the day is very short, averaging 6 hours and 41 minutes between sunrise and sunset at the winter solstice.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] As winter progresses, the length of the day grows fairly quickly, to 8 hours and 20 minutes by the end of January.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Around summer solstice, the days will be around 18 hours long, having 17 hours and 55 minutes between sunrise and sunset.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] During this time of the year marginal nautical twilight lasts the entire night.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Temperatures at this time of year hover around 17.0 °C (62.6 °F) during the day in most of the urban area, though nearer 16.0 °C (60.8 °F) directly on the coast, and around 18.0 to 19.0 °C (64.4 to 66.2 °F) in the westernmost suburbs.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Two weather stations collect climate data for the area, Aberdeen/Dyce Airport, and Craibstone.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Both are about 4+1⁄2 miles (7 km) to the northwest of the city centre, and given that they are in close proximity to each other, exhibit very similar climatic regimes.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Dyce tends to have marginally warmer daytime temperatures year-round owing to its slightly lower elevation, though it is more susceptible to harsh frosts.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The coldest temperature to occur in recent years was −16.8 °C (1.8 °F) during December 2010, while the following winter, Dyce set a new February high-temperature station record on 28 February 2012 of 17.2 °C (63.0 °F), and a new March high temperature record of 21.6 °C (70.9 °F) on 25 March 2012.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The average temperature of the sea ranges from 6.6 °C (43.9 °F) in March to 13.8 °C (56.8 °F) in August.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen locality population estimate is 198,590 (2020).
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] For the wider settlement of Aberdeen including Cove Bay and Dyce, the population estimate is 220,690 (2020).
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] For Aberdeen City council area, the population estimate is 231,780 (2024).
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] In 1396, the population was about 3,000.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The 2011 census showed fewer young people in Aberdeen, with 16.4% under 16, as opposed to the national average of 19.2%.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] According to the 2011 census Aberdeen is 91.9% white, ethnically, 24.7% were born outside Scotland, higher than the national average of 16%.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Of this population, 7.6% were born in other parts of the UK.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] 8.2% of Aberdonians stated to be from an ethnic minority (non-white) in the 2011 census, with 9,519 (4.3%) being Asian, with 3,385 (1.5%) coming from India and 2,187 (1.0%) being Chinese.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The city has around 5,610 (2.6%) residents of African or Caribbean origin, which is a higher percentage than both Glasgow and Edinburgh.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] In the household, there were 97,013 individual dwellings recorded in the city, of which 61% were privately owned, 9% privately rented and 23% rented from the council.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The most popular type of dwellings are apartments which comprise 49% of residences followed by semi-detached at just below 22%.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The median income of a household in the city is £16,813 (the mean income is £20,292) (2005) which places approximately 18% households in the city below the poverty line (defined as 60% of the mean income).
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Conversely, an Aberdeen postcode has the second highest number of millionaires of any postcode in the UK.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The proportion of people residing in Aberdeen born outside the UK was 21.1% in 2022, compared with 15.9% in 2011 and 6.3% in 2001.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Below are the fifteen largest overseas-born groups in Aberdeen according to the 2022 census, alongside the two previous censuses.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Christianity is the main religion practised in the city.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's largest denominations are the Church of Scotland (through the Presbytery of Aberdeen) and the Roman Catholic Church, both with numerous churches across the city, with the Scottish Episcopal Church having the third-largest number.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The census in 2022 showed that Aberdeen has the highest proportion of non-religious residents of any city in Scotland, with 58% of citizens claiming to have no religion.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] In the Middle Ages, the Kirk of St Nicholas was the only burgh kirk and one of Scotland's largest parish churches.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Like a number of other Scottish kirks, it was subdivided after the Reformation, in this case into the East and West churches.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] At that time, the city also was home to houses of the Carmelites (Whitefriars) and Franciscans (Greyfriars).
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The latter survives in modified form as the chapel of Marischal College.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] St Machar's Cathedral was built twenty years after David I (1124–1153) transferred the pre-Reformation diocese from Mortlach in Banffshire to Old Aberdeen in 1137.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Except the episcopate of William Elphinstone (1484–1511), building progressed slowly.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Gavin Dunbar, who followed him in 1518, completed the structure by adding the two western spires and the southern transept.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] It is now a congregation of the Church of Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Mary's Cathedral is a Roman Catholic cathedral in Gothic style, erected in 1859.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Andrew's Cathedral serves the Scottish Episcopal Church.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] It was constructed in 1817 as Archibald Simpson's first commission and contains a memorial to the consecration of the first bishop of the Episcopal Church in the United States of America, which took place nearby.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] In 1804, St Peter's Church, the first permanent Roman Catholic church in the city after the Reformation was built.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Numerous other Protestant denominations have a presence in Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The Salvation Army citadel on the Castlegate dominates the view of the east end of Union Street.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there is a Unitarian church, established in 1833 and located in Skene Terrace.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Christadelphians have been present in Aberdeen since at least 1844.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Over the years, they have rented space to meet at a number of locations and currently meet in the Inchgarth Community Centre in Garthdee.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Quaker meetinghouse on Crown Street, the only purpose built Friends meeting house in Scotland that is still in use today.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there are a number of Baptist congregations in the city, and Evangelical congregations have been appearing in significant numbers since the late 2000s.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The city also has two meeting houses of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (LDS Church).
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] There are also four mosques in Aberdeen which serve the Islamic community in the city.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] There is an Orthodox Jewish Synagogue established in 1945.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Thai Buddhist temple located in the Hazelhead area of the city.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] There are no formal Hindu buildings, although there is a fortnightly Hindu religious gathering on the first and third Sunday afternoons at Queens Cross Parish church hall.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen has a small Baháʼí society.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,756 residents aged three and over, 76,650 (35.2%) considered themselves able to speak or read the Scots language.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,760 residents aged three and over, 2,919 (1.3%) considered themselves able to speak or read Gaelic.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Traditionally, Aberdeen was home to fishing, textile mills, shipbuilding and paper-making.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] These industries have been largely replaced.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] High technology developments in the electronics design and development industry, research in agriculture and fishing and the oil industry, which have been largely responsible for Aberdeen's economic growth, are now major parts of Aberdeen's economy.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Until the 1970s, most of Aberdeen's leading industries dated from the 18th century; mainly these were textiles, foundry work, shipbuilding and paper-making, the oldest industry in the city, with paper having been first made there in 1694.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Paper-making has reduced in importance since the closures of Donside Paper Mill in 2001 and the Davidson Mill in 2005 leaving the Stoneywood Paper Mill with a workforce of approximately 500.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Textile production ended in 2004 when Richards of Aberdeen closed.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Grey granite was quarried at Rubislaw quarry for more than 300 years, and used for paving setts, kerb and building stones, and monumental and other ornamental pieces.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen granite was used to build the terraces of the Houses of Parliament and Waterloo Bridge in London.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The current owners have begun pumping 40 years of rainwater from the quarry to develop a heritage centre on the site.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] In-shore fishing was once the predominant industry but was surpassed by deep-sea fisheries, which derived a great impetus from improved technologies throughout the 20th century.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Catches have fallen because of overfishing and the use of the harbour by oil support vessels, and so although still an important fishing port it is now eclipsed by the more northerly ports of Peterhead and Fraserburgh.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The Fisheries Research Services are headquartered in Aberdeen, and there is a marine research laboratory there.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is well regarded for the agricultural and soil research carried out at The James Hutton Institute (formerly the Macaulay Land Use Research Institute), which has close links to the city's two universities.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The Rowett Research Institute is a world-renowned research centre for studies into food and nutrition located in Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] It has produced three Nobel laureates and there is a high concentration of life scientists working in the city.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] As oil reserves in the North Sea decrease, there is an effort to rebrand Aberdeen as the **energy capital of Europe** rather than the oil capital, and there is interest in the development of new energy sources, and technology transfer from oil into renewable energy and other industries is underway.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The "Energetica" initiative led by Scottish Enterprise has been designed to accelerate this process.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has become a major world centre for undersea petroleum technology.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen had been a major maritime centre throughout the 19th century, when a group of local entrepreneurs launched the first steam-powered trawler.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The steam trawling industry expanded and by 1933 Aberdeen was Scotland's top fishing port, employing nearly 3,000 men with 300 vessels sailing from its harbour.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] By the time oil was coming on stream, much of the trawling fleet had relocated to Peterhead.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Geologists had speculated about oil and gas in the North Sea since the middle of the 20th century, but tapping its deep and inhospitable waters was another story.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] With the Middle Eastern oil sheiks becoming more aware of the political and economic power of their oil reserves and government threats of rationing, the industry began to consider the North Sea as a viable source of oil.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Exploration commenced in the 1960s and the first major find in the British sector was in November 1970 in the Forties field, 110 miles (180 km) east of Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] By late 1975, after years of intense construction, the necessary infrastructure was in place.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Oil flowed through the Forties pipeline system directly to the refinery at far-away Grangemouth.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] In 2011, the Centre for Cities named Aberdeen as the best-placed city for growth in Britain, as the country looked to emerge from the recent economic downturn.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] With energy still providing the backbone of the local economy, recent years have seen very large new investment in the North Sea owing to rising oil prices and favourable government tax incentives.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] This has led to several oil majors and independents building new global offices in the city.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Five of Scotland's top ten businesses are based in Aberdeen with a collective turnover of £14 billion, yielding a profit in excess of £2.4 billion.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Alongside this 29 of Scotland's top 100 businesses are located in Aberdeen with an employment rate of 77.9%, making it the second highest UK city for employment.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Figures released in 2016 ranked Aberdeen as having the second highest number of patents processed per person in the UK.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The traditional shopping streets are Union Street and George Street, now complemented by shopping centres, including the Bon Accord Centre and the Trinity Shopping Centre.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] A £190 million retail development, Union Square, reached completion in late September/early October 2009.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Major retail parks away from the city centre include the Berryden Retail Park, the Kittybrewster Retail Park and the Beach Boulevard Retail Park.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Market has been rebuilt twice, but closed in 2020.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] In March 2004, Aberdeen was awarded Fairtrade City status by the Fairtrade Foundation.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's architecture is known for its principal use during the Victorian era of granite, which has led to its local nickname of the Granite City.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] In Castle Street, a continuation eastwards of Union Street, is the new Aberdeen Town House, a very prominent landmark in Aberdeen, built between 1868 and 1873 to a design by Peddie and Kinnear.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Alexander Marshall Mackenzie's extension to Marischal College on Broad Street, opened by King Edward VII in 1906, created the second largest granite building in the world (after the Escorial, Madrid).
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has long been famous for its 45 parks and gardens, and citywide floral displays which include two million roses, eleven million daffodils and three million crocuses.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The city has won the Royal Horticultural Society's Britain in Bloom 'Best City' award ten times, the overall Scotland in Bloom competition twenty times and the large city category every year since 1968.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] However, despite recent spurious reports, Aberdeen has never been banned from the Britain in Bloom competition.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The city won the 2006 Scotland in Bloom "Best City" award along with the International Cities in Bloom award.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The suburb of Dyce also won the Small Towns award.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Duthie Park opened in 1883 on the north bank of the River Dee.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] It was named after and given to the city by Miss Elizabeth Crombie Duthie of Ruthrieston in 1881.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Hazlehead Park, is large and forested, and located on the outskirts of the city.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Johnston Gardens is a small park of one hectare in the west end of the city.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] In 2002, the garden was named the best garden in the British Islands.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Seaton Park, formerly the grounds of a private house, is on the edge of the grounds of St Machar's Cathedral and was acquired for the city in 1947.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has hosted several theatres throughout its history, some of which have been converted or destroyed.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Today, all railway services to the south run via Dundee.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The faster main line from Aberdeen to Perth via Forfar and Strathmore closed in 1967, as a result of the Beeching cuts; the faster main line from Perth to Edinburgh via Glenfarg also closed subsequently in 1970.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] A second station, at Dyce, serves the north of the city centre; it is on the Aberdeen–Inverness line.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] First Aberdeen operates the majority of city bus services, as the successor to Grampian Regional Transport (GRT) and Aberdeen Corporation Tramways.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Secondary operators include Stagecoach Bluebird and Stagecoach South Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is the global headquarters of parent company FirstGroup, having grown from the GRT Group.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] First is still based at the former Aberdeen Tramways depot on King Street, which has now been redeveloped into a new headquarters and bus depot.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] On 18 April 2025, the "Aberdeen Adventurer" tour bus scheme ran by McGill's Bus Services was launched with 10 stops around the city on a 75-minute loop.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Stops include King's College, Pittodrie Stadium and the Aberdeen Art Gallery with the service due to end on 20 September 2026.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen International Airport (ABZ), sited in Dyce in the north of the city, serves domestic and international destinations in France, the Netherlands, Spain, Ireland and Scandinavian countries.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The heliport, which serves the oil industry and rescue services, is one of the world's busiest commercial heliports.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is connected to the UK's National Cycle Network; it has a track to the south, connecting to cities including Dundee and Edinburgh, and one to the north that forks about 10 miles (15 km) from the city into two different tracks heading to Inverness and Fraserburgh respectively.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Two popular shared-use paths, along old railway lines, are the Deeside Way to Banchory (which will eventually connect to Ballater) and the Formartine and Buchan Way to Ellon, both used by a mixture of cyclists, walkers and occasionally horses.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] In May 2026, a self-service e-bike hire scheme was introduced in Aberdeen, operated by Voi Technology.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Some 350 bikes are available on a pay-as-you-go basis.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The scheme replaced an earlier bike hire scheme which was operated between 2022 and 2024 by *The Big Issue* and Sharebike but which was scrapped because of funding issues as well as vandalism.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Harbour is important as the largest in the north of Scotland and serves the ferry route to Orkney and Shetland.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Established in 1136, the harbour has been referred to as the "oldest business in Britain".
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The Dee Estuary, Aberdeen's harbour, started out as a fishing port, moving on to steam trawlers and serving the oil industry; it is now a major port of departure for the Baltic and Scandinavia.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has two universities, the ancient University of Aberdeen, and Robert Gordon University, a modern university often referred to as RGU.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has a high proportion of students of 11.5%, higher than the national average of 7%.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen began as King's College, Aberdeen, which was founded in 1495 by William Elphinstone (1431–1514), Bishop of Aberdeen and Chancellor of Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Marischal College, a separate institution, was founded in New Aberdeen by George Keith, fifth Earl Marischal of Scotland in 1593.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] These institutions were merged by the Universities (Scotland) Act 1858 to form the University of Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The university is the fifth oldest in the English-speaking world and offers degrees in a full range of disciplines.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Its main campus is in Old Aberdeen in the north of the city and it currently has approximately 14,000 students.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The university's debating society is the oldest in Scotland, founded in 1848 as the King's College Debating Society.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Today, Aberdeen is consistently ranked among the top 200 universities in the world and is ranked within the top 20 universities in the United Kingdom.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was also named the 2019 Scottish University of the Year by The Times and Sunday Times Good University Guide.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] In early 2022, Aberdeen opened the Science Teaching Hub.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Robert Gordon's College (originally Robert Gordon's Hospital) was founded in 1750 by the merchant Robert Gordon, grandson of the map maker Robert Gordon of Straloch, and was further endowed in 1816 by Alexander Simpson of Collyhill.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Originally devoted to the instruction and maintenance of the sons of poor burgesses of guild and trade in the city, it was reorganised in 1881 as a day and night school for secondary and technical education.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] In 1903, the vocational education component of the college was designated a Central Institution and was renamed as the Robert Gordon Institute of Technology in 1965.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] In 1992, university status was awarded and it became Robert Gordon University.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The university has expanded and developed significantly in recent years, and was named Best Modern University in the UK for 2012 by *The Sunday Times*.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] It was previously *The Sunday Times* Scottish University of the Year for 2011, primarily because of its record on graduate employment.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is also home to two artistic schools: Gray's School of Art, founded in 1886, which is one of the oldest established colleges of art in the UK.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Scott Sutherland School of Architecture and Built Environment, was one of the first architectural schools to have its training courses recognised by the Royal Institute of British Architects.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Both are now part of Robert Gordon University and are based at its Garthdee campus.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] North East Scotland College has several campuses in the city and offers a wide variety of part-time and full-time courses leading to several different qualifications in science.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Agricultural College is based just outside Aberdeen, on the Craibstone Estate.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] This is situated beside the roundabout for Aberdeen Airport on the A96.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The college provides three services—Learning, Research and Consultancy.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The college features many land-based courses such as Agriculture, Countryside Management, Sustainable Environmental Management and Rural Business Management.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] There are a variety of courses from diplomas to master's degrees.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The Marine Laboratory Aberdeen, which specialises in fisheries, Macaulay Land Use Research Institute (soil science), and the Rowett Research Institute (animal nutrition) are some other higher education institutions.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen College of Performing Arts also provides full-time Drama and Musical Theatre training at Further Education level.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] There are currently 15 secondary schools and 54 primary schools which are run by the city council.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] There are a number of private schools in Aberdeen: Robert Gordon's College, Albyn School, St Margaret's School for Girls, the International School of Aberdeen and a Waldorf/Steiner School.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] State secondary schools in Aberdeen include Aberdeen Grammar School, Bridge of Don Academy, Bucksburn Academy, Cults Academy, Dyce Academy, Harlaw Academy, Hazlehead Academy, Lochside Academy, Northfield Academy, Oldmachar Academy and St Machar Academy.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p01] Independent primary and secondary schools in Aberdeen include Albyn School, Robert Gordon's College, St Margaret's School for Girls, and the International School of Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The city has a wide range of cultural activities, amenities, and museums, and is regularly visited by Scotland's National Arts Companies.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] It was awarded the Nicholson Trophy for the best-kept town at the Britain in Bloom contest in 1975.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery houses a collection of Impressionist, Victorian, Scottish and 20th-century British paintings as well as collections of silver and glass.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] It also includes The Alexander Macdonald Bequest, a collection of late 19th-century works donated by the museum's first benefactor and a constantly changing collection of contemporary work and regular visiting exhibitions.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery reopened in 2019 after a four-year refurbishment costing £34.6m.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Maritime Museum, located in Shiprow, tells the story of Aberdeen's links with the sea from the days of sail and clipper ships to the latest oil and gas exploration technology.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] It includes an 8.5-metre-high (28 ft) model of the Murchison oil production platform and a 19th-century assembly taken from Rattray Head lighthouse Provost Ross' House is the second oldest dwelling house in the city.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] It was built in 1593 and became the residence of Provost John Ross of Arnage in 1702.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The house retains some original medieval features, including a kitchen, fireplaces and beam-and-board ceilings.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The Gordon Highlanders Museum tells the story of one of Scotland's best known regiments.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Provost Skene's House on Flourmill Lane dates from 1545 and is the oldest surviving townhouse in the city.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] It reopened in October 2021 after significant refurbishment costing £3.8m.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] One of the new exhibitions is a Hall of Heroes featuring 100 Aberdonians who have made a significant contribution to the city.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The Tollbooth Museum on the Castlegate (currently closed to visitors) is a former jail, which first opened as a public museum in 1995.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Treasure Hub is a storage facility for Aberdeen Museums and Galleries containing over 100,000 items.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The store is open for infrequent tours, for example as part of Doors Open Day.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Marischal Museum holds the principal collections of the University of Aberdeen, comprising some 80,000 items in the areas of fine art, Scottish history and archaeology, and European, Mediterranean and Near Eastern archaeology.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The permanent displays and reference collections are augmented by regular temporary exhibitions, and since its closure to the public it now has a virtual online presence It closed to the public in 2008.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The King's Museum acts as the main museum of the university now.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Student Show, performed annually without interruption since 1921, under the auspices of the Aberdeen Students' Charities Campaign, is the longest-running of its kind in the United Kingdom.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] It is written, produced and performed by students and graduates of Aberdeen's universities and higher education institutions.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Since 1929—other than on a handful of occasions—it has been staged at His Majesty's Theatre.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] National festivals which visited Aberdeen in 2012 included the British Science Festival in September, hosted by the University of Aberdeen but with events also taking place at Robert Gordon University and at other venues across the city.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] In February 2012 the University of Aberdeen also hosted the Inter Varsity Folk Dance Festival, the longest-running folk festival in the United Kingdom.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Spectra, an annual light festival hosted in different locations across the city.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Nuart, a festival showcasing street art around the city.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] In 2020, the WayWORD Festival was launched by the University of Aberdeen WORD centre for creative writing.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] This yearly programme celebrates the arts through readings, performances, workshops and discussion panels.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] There have been many notable headliners including Val McDermid, Irvine Welsh and Douglas Stuart (writer).
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Galas are held annually throughout the city, the most notable being the Culter Gala, which is usually held on the last Saturday of May.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The local dialect of Lowland Scots is often known as Doric and is spoken not just in the city, but across the northeast of Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] It differs somewhat from other Scots dialects: most noticeable are the pronunciation "f" for what is normally written "wh" and "ee" for what in standard English would usually be written "oo" (Scots "ui").
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Every year the annual Doric Festival takes place in Aberdeenshire to celebrate the history of the north-east's language.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Scotland's oldest newspaper the *Press and Journal*, a local and regional newspaper first published in 1747.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The *Press and Journal* and its sister paper the tabloid *Evening Express* are printed six days a week by Aberdeen Journals.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] There was one free newspaper, the *Aberdeen Citizen*.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] BBC Scotland has a network studio production base in the city's Beechgrove area, and BBC Aberdeen produces *The Beechgrove Potting Shed* for radio while Tern Television produces *The Beechgrove Garden*.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The city is also home to STV North (formerly Grampian Television), which produces the regional news programmes such as *STV News at Six*, as well as local commercials.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The station, based at Craigshaw Business Park in Tullos, was based at larger studios in Queens Cross from September 1961 until June 2003.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Music venues include the Music Hall and the P&J Live.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen region has given its name to a number of dishes, including the Aberdeen buttery (also known as "rowie") and Aberdeen Sausage.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] In 2015, a study was published in The Scotsman which analysed the presence of branded fast food outlets in Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Of the ten towns and cities analysed, Aberdeen was found to have the lowest per capita concentration, with just 0.12 stores per 1,000 inhabitants.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The public health service in Scotland, NHS Scotland provides for the people of Aberdeen through the NHS Grampian health board.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Albyn Hospital is a private hospital located in the west end of the city.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen City Council is responsible for city-owned infrastructure which is paid for by a mixture of Council Tax and income from the Scottish Government.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure and services run by the council include: nursery, primary and secondary education, roads, clearing snow in winter, city wardens, maintaining parks, refuse collection, economic development, public analyst, public mortuary, street cleaning and street lighting.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure in private hands includes electricity, gas and telecoms.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Water and sewerage services are provided by Scottish Water.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The first ever recorded game of football, was outlined by teacher David Wedderburn in his book "Vocabula" written in 1633, during his time teaching at Aberdeen Grammar School.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] There is one Aberdeen-based football club in the SPFL.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] (The Dons) play in the Scottish Premiership at Pittodrie Stadium.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The club won the European Cup Winners Cup and the European Super Cup in 1983, the Scottish Premier League Championship four times (1955, 1980, 1984 and 1985), and the Scottish Cup eight times (1947, 1970, 1982, 1983, 1984, 1986, 1990 and 2025).
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of Alex Ferguson, Aberdeen was a major force in British football during the 1980s.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of McInnes the team won the 2014 Scottish League Cup and followed it up with a second-place league finish for the first time in more than 20 years in the following season.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] But it was over the last few seasons that results stagnated and McInnes was replaced by former Aberdeen and Newcastle player Stephen Glass.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Cove Rangers, as of season 2024-25 play in League One, at the Balmoral Stadium in the suburb of Cove Bay.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Cove won the Highland Football League championship in 2001, 2008, 2009, 2013 and 2019, winning the League Two play-offs in 2019 and earning promotion.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] At the point at which the 2019/20 League Two season was curtailed due to the COVID-19 pandemic, Cove were sitting top of the League Two table and were promoted as Champions.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Other local teams include Banks o'Dee who play at Spain Park in the Highland Football League and members of the SJFA North Region; Culter, Dyce, Stoneywood Parkvale, Glentanar, Sunnybank Hall Russell United, Bridge of Don Thistle and Hermes.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen hosted Caledonia Reds, a Scottish rugby team, before they merged with the Glasgow Warriors in 1998.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] In 2005 the President of the SRU said it was hoped eventually to establish a professional team in Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] In November 2008 the city hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Canada, with Scotland winning 41–0.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] In November 2010 the city once again hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Samoa, with Scotland winning 19–16.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Warriors rugby league team play in the Rugby League Conference Division One.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The Warriors also run Under 15's and 17's teams.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Grammar School won the Saltire Schools Cup in 2011.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The Royal Aberdeen Golf Club, founded in 1780 is the sixth oldest golf club in the world, and hosted the Senior British Open in 2005, and the amateur team event the Walker Cup in 2011.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Royal Aberdeen also hosted the Scottish Open in 2014, won by Justin Rose.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The club has a second course, and there are public golf courses at Auchmill, Balnagask, Hazlehead and King's Links.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] There are new courses planned for the area, including world-class facilities with major financial backing, the city and shire are set to become important in golf tourism.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] In Summer 2012, Donald Trump opened a new state of the art golf course at Menie, just north of the city, as the Trump International Golf Links, Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Ice hockey in Aberdeen boasts a history that began in the early 20th century.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Glaciarium on Forbesfield Road became a hub for games, featuring teams like the Grammar School Former Pupils and the Aberdeen Ice Hockey Club.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] However, the sport all but died out with the onset of WW1.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The sport was revived in the city with the opening of the Linx Ice Arena in 1992.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Lynx plays in the Scottish National League and is based at the Linx Ice Arena.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Founded in 2005, they won back to back regular season titles in 2022-23 and 2023–24 and won the play-off championship in 2015-16 and again in 2024–25.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] They regularly sell out home games and are the second best supported sports team in the city after Aberdeen FC.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The City of Aberdeen Swim Team (COAST) was based in Northfield swimming pool, but since the opening of the Aberdeen Aquatics Centre in 2014, it is now based there, as it has a 50 m pool as opposed to the 25 m pool at Northfield.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The team comprises several smaller swimming clubs and has enjoyed success throughout Scotland and in international competitions.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Three of the team's swimmers qualified for the 2006 Commonwealth Games.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] There are four boat clubs that row on the River Dee: Aberdeen Boat Club (ABC), Aberdeen Schools Rowing Association (ASRA), Aberdeen University Boat Club (AUBC) and Robert Gordon University Boat Club (RGUBC).
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The city has one national league side, Stoneywood-Dyce.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Local "Grades" cricket has been played in Aberdeen since 1884.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeenshire were the 2009 and 2014 Scottish National Premier League and Scottish Cup Champions.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen University Shinty Club (Scottish Gaelic: Club Camanachd Oilthigh Obar Dheathain) is the oldest constituted shinty club in the world, dating back to 1861.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The city council operates public tennis courts in various parks including an indoor tennis centre at Westburn Park.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The Beach Leisure Centre is home to a climbing wall, gymnasium and a swimming pool.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] There are numerous swimming pools dotted around the city notably the largest, the Bon Accord Baths which closed down in 2008.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] In common with many other major towns and cities in the UK, Aberdeen has an active roller derby league, Granite City Roller Derby.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Roughnecks American football club is a new team that started in 2012 and is the first team that Aberdeen has witnessed since the Granite City Oilers that began in 1986 and were wound up in the mid-1990s.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Oilers Floorball Club was founded in 2007.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The club initially attracted a range of experienced Scandinavian and other European players who were studying in Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Since their formation, Aberdeen Oilers have played in the British Floorball Northern League and went on to win the league in the 2008/09 season.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The club played a major role in setting up a ladies league in Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The Oilers' ladies team ended up second in the first ladies league season (2008/09).
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] One of the earliest known disasters is the Storegga Slide in the mesolithic period in 6225–6170 BCE which caused tsunami waves to hit North sea coastal areas, with wave heights of 3-6 meters in the north east Scotland areas.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] In 1876, the River Dee ferryboat disaster took place when 32 people drowned in the mouth of the River Dee.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The 20th century includes a World War II disaster when in 1943, a Luftwaffe raid dropped 129 bombs on Aberdeen resulting in 125 deaths..
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] In 1964, a typhoid outbreak occurred with 400 cases and three fatalities.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] In 1983, the Aberdeen taxi driver George Murdoch was killed, the murder case is unsolved.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] In modern time, accidents have been related with offshore drilling.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] In 1988, the oil platform Piper Alpha, located 190 km north-east of Aberdeen, exploded and collapsed, killing 165.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The accident is the worst ever offshore oil and gas disaster in terms of lives lost.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Hazlehead Park contains a memorial to the crew. .
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] In 1995, Bristow Helicopters Flight 56C was struck by lightning and emergency landed in the sea.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] The 18 crew and passengers on board survived.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] In 2009, the Bond Offshore Helicopters Flight 85N crashed 20 km north-east of Peterhead, while returning from an oil platform to Aberdeen Airport.
[src:aberdeen-journals/aberdeen-p02] Johnston Gardens contains a memorial to the deceased.
[src:aberdeen-journals/beano-studios] DC Thomson launched Beano Studios in June 2016.
[src:aberdeen-journals/beano-studios] The launch included a revamp of the *Beano* comic's cover and logo, and the launch of the beano.com website.
[src:aberdeen-journals/beano-studios] Nigel Pickard joined as non-executive director and Emma Scott served as CEO until 2020, when she was succeeded by David Guppy.
[src:aberdeen-journals/beano-studios] The Beano.com website includes games, videos, articles, and news about celebrities.
[src:aberdeen-journals/beano-studios] According to Mike Stirling, then Head of Beano Studios Scotland, the website aimed to be "a fun but trusted babysitter".
[src:aberdeen-journals/beano-studios] The website gained over two million visitors per year and is credited with increasing comic sales by 10% in 2018.
[src:aberdeen-journals/beano-studios] Beano Studios produced the 3D-animated series *Dennis & Gnasher: Unleashed!* for CBBC, which premiered in November 2017.
[src:aberdeen-journals/beano-studios] The series was distributed internationally by Jetpack and was sold to over 90 territories.
[src:aberdeen-journals/beano-studios] Other projects included a live-action *Minnie the Minx* series titled *The Magnificent Misadventures of Minnie* announced in 2018 and a *Bananaman* cartoon announced by Fox Entertainment in 2021.
[src:aberdeen-journals/brightsolid] The company began as a branch of the Thomson family business when William Thomson became the sole proprietor of Charles Alexander & Company, publishers of *Dundee Courier and Daily Argus*.
[src:aberdeen-journals/brightsolid] In 1884, David Couper Thomson took over the publishing business, and established it as D.C.
[src:aberdeen-journals/brightsolid] The firm flourished, and took its place as the third J in the "Three Js", the traditional summary of Dundee industry ("jute, jam and journalism").
[src:aberdeen-journals/brightsolid] Thomson was notable for his conservatism, vigorously opposing the introduction of trade unions into his workforce, and for refusing to employ Catholics.
[src:aberdeen-journals/brightsolid] By 2010, the company was producing more than 100 million comics, magazines, and newspapers every year from offices in Dundee, Glasgow, Manchester, and London.
[src:aberdeen-journals/brightsolid] In June 2010, 350 jobs at DC Thomson were made redundant with the closure of the West Ward Printworks in Dundee, along with a section of the Kingsway Print Plant.
[src:aberdeen-journals/brightsolid] Although the principal offices are now located outside Dundee city centre at Kingsway, the Courier Building at Meadowside has been retained as the company headquarters.
[src:aberdeen-journals/brightsolid] This 1902 building was designed to resemble an American red stone, steel reinforced office block.
[src:aberdeen-journals/brightsolid] When a nine-storey tower extension was added in 1960, the architect T.
[src:aberdeen-journals/brightsolid] The building underwent extensive renovation and reopened to employees in 2017, and is able to accommodate 600 workers.
[src:aberdeen-journals/brightsolid] In 2009 DC Thomson acquired the magazine company This England Publishing, which included *This England* magazine and *Evergreen* quarterly magazine.
[src:aberdeen-journals/brightsolid] In the same year DC Thomson acquired the Friends Reunited website from ITV for £25.6m, but by 2011 it was valued at £5.2m and was eventually shut down completely in February 2016.
[src:aberdeen-journals/brightsolid] In 2013, DC Thomson laid off 46 production staff at its Lang Stracht base in Aberdeen after printing was moved to Dundee.
[src:aberdeen-journals/brightsolid] As of 2016, the company posted an increase in pre-tax profits and revenue whilst employing over 2,000 workers.
[src:aberdeen-journals/brightsolid] Despite the falling circulation of newspapers and magazines, DC Thomson attributed the rising profits to company-wide cuts to operating costs and good figures in digital revenues and events.
[src:aberdeen-journals/brightsolid] The company went on to say that they would continue to branch out their brand into new areas to support the traditional newspaper and magazine divisions.
[src:aberdeen-journals/brightsolid] In February 2023, it was announced that several "well-loved" titles would be closed and employees would be made redundant as part of a wider restructuring.
[src:aberdeen-journals/brightsolid] On 9 February 2023, it was announced that *Shout*, *Living*, *Platinum Magazine*, *Evergreen*, *Animals & You* and *Animal Planet* would be closed with 300 employees being made redundant.
[src:aberdeen-journals/brightsolid] In January 2024, the company announced plans to eliminate 55 jobs and shutter four titles: *This England*, *My Weekly Pocket Novels*, *110% Gaming* and *Unicorn Universe*.
[src:aberdeen-journals/brightsolid] Brightsolid is a data centre and cloud-based hosting company based in Dundee that DC Thomson established in 1995 as Scotland Online.
[src:aberdeen-journals/brightsolid] It became Brightsolid in 2008, organised into two divisions: Brightsolid Online Publishing (BSOP) and Brightsolid Online Technology (BSOT).
[src:aberdeen-journals/brightsolid] The two divisions were split into separate businesses in October 2013, and Brightsolid Online Publishing was renamed DC Thomson Family History, with Annelies van den Belt as chief executive.
[src:aberdeen-journals/brightsolid] Findmypast Limited (formerly DC Thomson Family History, until 2015) owns a variety of large genealogy sites worldwide, including Findmypast, Genes Reunited and Mocavo.
[src:aberdeen-journals/brightsolid] The company had contracts to digitise archives for the Imperial War Museum and the British Library, where it was making the British Newspaper Archive searchable.
[src:aberdeen-journals/brightsolid] DC Thomson once owned Bridlington-based children's publisher Peter Haddock until they closed it in late 2013.
[src:aberdeen-journals/british-newspaper-archive] The **British Newspaper Archive** website provides access to searchable digitised archives of British and Irish newspapers.
[src:aberdeen-journals/british-newspaper-archive] The British Library's Newspapers section was based in Colindale in north London until 2013, and is now divided between the St Pancras and Boston Spa sites.
[src:aberdeen-journals/british-newspaper-archive] The library has an almost complete collection of British and Irish newspapers since 1840.
[src:aberdeen-journals/british-newspaper-archive] This is partly because of the legal deposit legislation of 1869, which required newspapers to supply a copy of each edition of a newspaper to the library.
[src:aberdeen-journals/british-newspaper-archive] London editions of national daily and Sunday newspapers are complete back to 1801.
[src:aberdeen-journals/british-newspaper-archive] In total, the collection consists of 660,000 bound volumes and 370,000 reels of microfilm containing tens of millions of newspapers with 52,000 titles on 45 km of shelves.
[src:aberdeen-journals/british-newspaper-archive] After the closure of Colindale in November 2013, access to the 750 million original printed pages was maintained via an automated and climate-controlled storage facility in Boston Spa, which opened in April 2014.
[src:aberdeen-journals/british-newspaper-archive] Printed pages which are available to subscribers include news articles covering issues of local and regional importance, family notices, letters to editors written by newspaper readers, obituaries and advertisements.
[src:aberdeen-journals/british-newspaper-archive] As of 2025, it is owned by the family history company Findmypast, which is part of DC Thomson.
[src:aberdeen-journals/british-newspaper-archive] In May 2010, a ten-year programme of digitisation of the newspaper archives with commercial partner DC Thomson subsidiary Brightsolid began.
[src:aberdeen-journals/british-newspaper-archive] In November 2011, BBC News reported on the launch of the British Newspaper Archive, an initiative to facilitate online access to over one million pages of pre-20th century newspapers.
[src:aberdeen-journals/british-newspaper-archive] The same newspapers from this partnership have also been made available to view on Findmypast and Genes Reunited.
[src:aberdeen-journals/british-newspaper-archive] As well as scanning of original paper copy, the project also scanned from microfilm copies that had been created by the British Library over the years.
[src:aberdeen-journals/british-newspaper-archive] The digitisation project established an online search facility that people could consult without having to visit the British Library newspaper depository in person.
[src:aberdeen-journals/british-newspaper-archive] In 2021, Findmypast and the British Library announced an extension of their long-term partnership in the British Newspaper Archive.
[src:aberdeen-journals/british-newspaper-archive] They said that a further 14 million pages would be added to the online archive over the following three years, including 1 million free-to-access pages each year.
[src:aberdeen-journals/british-newspaper-archive] Among the collections are the Thomason Tracts, containing 7,200 17th-century news pamphlets and newsbooks, and the Burney Collection, featuring nearly 1 million pages of newspapers from the late eighteenth century and early nineteenth century.
[src:aberdeen-journals/british-newspaper-archive] The Thomason Tracts and Burney collections are held at St Pancras, and are available in digital facsimile.
[src:aberdeen-journals/british-newspaper-archive] The section also has extensive records of non-British newspapers in languages that use the Latin and Cyrillic alphabets.
[src:aberdeen-journals/british-newspaper-archive] The library's substantial holdings of newspapers in the languages of Asia and the Middle East may be accessed at the library's reading rooms at St.
[src:aberdeen-journals/british-newspaper-archive] On 29 May 2025, earlier editions of the *News Letter* dating back to October 1738 were added to the website.
[src:aberdeen-journals/british-newspaper-archive] Access within the British Library is free.
[src:aberdeen-journals/british-newspaper-archive] Starting in 2021, some newspaper pages from the years 1720–1880 are free to view online.
[src:aberdeen-journals/british-newspaper-archive] Full online access is by subscription, based on daily or item charges, £14.99 for one month or £8.34 per month for an annual subscription, as of December 2024.
[src:aberdeen-journals/british-newspaper-archive] New visitors may access three free page views and explore hundreds of national, regional and local titles dating from the 1700s–2000s.
[src:aberdeen-journals/british-newspaper-archive] Reviews of the service have been mixed, with some early responses complimentary about the ability to access and search the large data sets.
[src:aberdeen-journals/british-newspaper-archive] However, there have been complaints of the excessive cost and the general policy of the British Library allowing a private company the rights to the newspapers.
[src:aberdeen-journals/british-newspaper-archive] One writer noted that: "The BNA demonstrates what happens to our cultural heritage when there is no political will for public investment.
[src:aberdeen-journals/british-newspaper-archive] The search interface has also been criticised for problems in identifying where the searched terms are on the retrieved pages, and in the unreliability of the web interface, with bugs preventing images loading and regular crashes.
[src:aberdeen-journals/bunty-p01] With the issue of 28 March 1992 (issue #1785), *Bunty*'s covers switched from illustrated comics-style imagery to a photograph of a teen model, becoming more evocative of a fashion magazine than a comic book.
[src:aberdeen-journals/bunty-p01] *Bunty* went monthly in 2000 before ceasing publication after a further 5 months; altogether the magazine published 2,249 issues.
[src:aberdeen-journals/bunty-p01] As well as the weekly comic, Christmas and summer annuals were published.
[src:aberdeen-journals/bunty-p01] After the weekly comic ended its publication in 2001, the Christmas annuals continued to be published until 2008.
[src:aberdeen-journals/bunty-p01] Due to a lack of new comic strips to be included, the annuals post-2001 focused more on typical girls' magazine features, like horoscope quizzes and celebrity facts.
[src:aberdeen-journals/bunty-p01] The annuals ceased their regular publication with the 2009 issue, although several one-off books featuring reprints of the classic Bunty comics have since been released.
[src:aberdeen-journals/bunty-p01] The average issue of *Bunty* contained several short comic-strip stories, broken up by letters pages, competitions, featured readers, puzzle pages, promotions, next-week previews or advertisements.
[src:aberdeen-journals/bunty-p01] The back page initially featured a cut-out doll and paper clothes, which eventually gave way to a wall poster.
[src:aberdeen-journals/bunty-p01] A one-page feature included a short comic strip about the comic's namesake, a blonde girl called Bunty, and her friends Haya and Payal.
[src:aberdeen-journals/bunty-p01] The strip was so short it usually could not convey more than a quick joke — mostly about normal teenage girl subjects like boys, family, or school.
[src:aberdeen-journals/bunty-p01] This story was written out as a diary, with pictures to accompany it.
[src:aberdeen-journals/bunty-p01] The pictures took the form of photographs, being the only regular comic to do so (although regularly "one-time" comics also took the form of being shown in photographs).
[src:aberdeen-journals/bunty-p01] Regularly her stories would consist of her writing about people, boyfriends, and situations she was in with her friends — although sometimes she would have a story set about her, with an adventure such as finding good Christmas cards.
[src:aberdeen-journals/bunty-p01] Her friends' names changed from issue to issue, the only regular characters being her brother and her mother.
[src:aberdeen-journals/bunty-p01] A comic drawn very much in the same way as *The Four Marys*, this was set in a mixed-sex comprehensive school.
[src:aberdeen-journals/bunty-p01] *The Comp* was originally published in *Nikki*, and moved to *Bunty* in 1989 after that comic folded.
[src:aberdeen-journals/bunty-p01] *The Comp* finished a short time before *Bunty*'s end, the story being that Redvale Comprehensive closed down and the pupils were sent to different schools.
[src:aberdeen-journals/bunty-p01] A comic drawn in much the same way as *The Comp* and *The Four Marys*, *Penny's Place* began in the comic *M&J* (an amalgamation of earlier comics, *Mandy* and *Judy*), but was taken up by *Bunty* in 1997 when *M&J* ended.
[src:aberdeen-journals/bunty-p01] The story centered on Penny, whose parents owned a cafe called Penny's Place, and her three best friends, who all lived in the same town and attended the same school.
[src:aberdeen-journals/bunty-p01] Penny's best friend Donna was from a lower-class family and had several brothers and sisters, and these siblings were often involved in storylines.
[src:aberdeen-journals/bunty-p01] The story came to an end in the late 1990s, but due to popular demand *Bunty* began to publish the story again from the beginning.
[src:aberdeen-journals/bunty-p01] During this time, both *Bunty* and *Mandy* published *Penny's Place* in their Christmas annuals.
[src:aberdeen-journals/bunty-p02] The lyrics to the song "Melody Lee" by the British punk rock group the Damned, on their 1979 album *Machine Gun Etiquette*, were borrowed entirely from the dialogue balloons of *Bunty* comics.
[src:aberdeen-journals/bunty-p02] On 19 March 2012, the Royal Mail launched a special stamp collection to celebrate Britain's rich comic book history.
[src:aberdeen-journals/bunty-p02] The collection featured *The Beano, The Dandy, Eagle, The Topper, Roy of the Rovers, Bunty, Buster, Valiant, Twinkle* and *2000 AD*.
[src:aberdeen-journals/classics-from-the-comics] The comic had 64 pages, and the front cover depicted many of the characters in one group activity, drawn from September 1997 to May 2006 by Anthony Caluori.
[src:aberdeen-journals/classics-from-the-comics] In 2006, the cover was redesigned to show "Classics from the Comics" with a roundel containing Korky the Cat's head and the words Classics Collection, and a large illustration by Ken H.
[src:aberdeen-journals/classics-from-the-comics] The new editor started penning a letter to the readers on the contents page, and the advert and original strip on the inside and back covers were replaced by further reprinted strips, which are always Korky the Cat and Biffo the Bear.
[src:aberdeen-journals/classics-from-the-comics] A small notice was published on all the pages, identifying which comic the strip comes from (Classic *Beano*, Classic *Dandy*, etc.).
[src:aberdeen-journals/classics-from-the-comics] Near the end of each issue, a "Readers Requests" postal address was displayed, so readers could write to DC Thomson and request other archive strips to go in a future issue.
[src:aberdeen-journals/classics-from-the-comics] Free gifts in the form of *The Fun Size Beanos* or *The Fun Size Dandys* were featured in early issues, plus free gifts originally given away with *The Beano* or *The Dandy*.
[src:aberdeen-journals/classics-from-the-comics] In July 2004 *Classics from the Comics* celebrated its 100th issue, revamping the front cover at the same time, changing the logo from a plain serif font to a sans-serif one with a 3-D effect.
[src:aberdeen-journals/classics-from-the-comics] The August 2008 issue was a *Beano* special, featuring only characters from that 70-year-old comic.
[src:aberdeen-journals/classics-from-the-comics] It featured the oldest (Ping the Elastic Man and Deep Down Daddy Neptune, 1938), and most recent stories (specifically the picture of Dennis, Gnasher, Wallace & Gromit from the *Beano* printed only the previous day; the most recent actual story was "Crazy for Daisy" from 2003) ever used.
[src:aberdeen-journals/classics-from-the-comics] For this issue, the usual Korky roundel was replaced with the logo from the *70 Years of Fun* collector's edition.
[src:aberdeen-journals/classics-from-the-comics] Ltd's *Golden Years*/*60 Years*/*70 Years* books, which are brought out each Christmas, are effectively *Classic From the Comics'* annual, although they started in 1988, eight years before Classics launched.
[src:aberdeen-journals/classics-from-the-comics] Despite a further 'retro' relaunch in the spring of 2010, *Classics from the Comics* ended that October, the final issue being number 175.
